This paper studies information aggregation in networks, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of networks and graph theory suggests that cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a likely sub-category. The study of dynamics and algorithms in networks suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely sub-category. The focus on tree structures and preferential attachment models suggests that cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the use of probability and information theory suggests that cs.IT (Information Theory) is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
